hands_on_practices.problem:
A dermatology and venereology service is validating a point-of-care Reverse Transcription Polymerase Chain Reaction (RT-PCR) assay for Hand, Foot, and Mouth Disease (HFMD) against a laboratory RT-PCR, which is treated as a reference standard. In a consecutively enrolled cohort of $N = 1000$ children with clinically suspected HFMD, the following $2 \times 2$ confusion matrix was obtained, with counts defined by clinical epidemiology convention (true positives are those positive by both assays, false negatives are positive by laboratory RT-PCR but negative by point-of-care RT-PCR, false positives are negative by laboratory RT-PCR but positive by point-of-care RT-PCR, and true negatives are negative by both assays):
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
\text{TP} & \text{FN} \\
\text{FP} & \text{TN}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
294 & 26 \\
34 & 646
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Starting from the foundational definitions that connect test outcomes to disease status in diagnostic epidemiology and the probabilistic definition of inter-rater agreement, derive and compute the sensitivity, specificity, positive predictive value (PPV), negative predictive value (NPV), and Cohen’s $\kappa$ statistic for agreement between the point-of-care RT-PCR and the laboratory RT-PCR. Express all five quantities as decimals and round your answers to four significant figures. No units are required.
